<br>
You may objectify them to the same thing but i suspect most people would read these two sentences differently:<br>
<br>
&quot;he was being greedy&quot;<br>
&quot;he wanted that&quot;<br>
<br>
It seems like symantics but clearly by the differing viewpoints some use greed with negative inclination.  <br>
<br>
<br>
Greed n. the negative personification of want<br>
<br>
or something might be a definition.   <br>
<br>
Notice i didnt quote websters.  The key here isnt the dictionary defintion or the &quot;correct&quot; definition but rather the implied defintion in actual use.<br>
<br>
there can be no doubt that most people have some sort of concept of negative in greed.   If by applied definition has a negative component then objectively white washing it into another word for &quot;want&quot; will never fly in persuasive argument.<br>
<br>
